00:23:10.420 --> 00:23:11.410
It is very good.

00:23:11.770 --> 00:23:15.350
For our use case,
we're going to stick with this for now.

00:23:17.240 --> 00:23:18.920
Now I want to talk about,

00:23:19.020 --> 00:23:22.820
and now this is the only time that
I'm bringing theory into this.

00:23:23.280 --> 00:23:26.020
I want to talk about affordances
because this is now

00:23:26.120 --> 00:23:27.800
important for the next part.

00:23:28.960 --> 00:23:31.000
This is a term that comes up often.

00:23:31.150 --> 00:23:32.360
I'm studying

00:23:32.360 --> 00:23:35.630
for a certification right now
and this is a concept that comes up often

00:23:36.370 --> 00:23:40.740
and it says-- It's defined
as a design affordance is a clue

00:23:40.840 --> 00:23:44.910
about how an object should be used,

00:23:45.010 --> 00:23:48.240
typically provided by the object itself
or its context.

00:23:48.410 --> 00:23:54.080
This is a quote by Sheri

00:23:54.180 --> 00:23:58.150
Byrne-Haber,
who is an accessibility specialist.

00:23:59.260 --> 00:24:01.220
Link is also in the slide.

00:24:02.960 --> 00:24:05.900
Basically what that means
is that you see a thing

00:24:06.300 --> 00:24:08.560
and you intuitively know
what to do with the thing

00:24:09.570 --> 00:24:13.470
and this is really important for something
that is supposed to be interactive.

00:24:13.570 --> 00:24:15.200
People have to know what to do with it.

00:24:15.940 --> 00:24:19.950
I think in our example,

00:24:21.880 --> 00:24:24.950
it's quite clear,
it's a blog article

00:24:25.040 --> 00:24:27.350
and people should be able to click on it

00:24:27.820 --> 00:24:30.000
and they should know I can click on it.

00:24:31.390 --> 00:24:33.310
It is the most important
affordance for cards

00:24:33.440 --> 00:24:37.390
is probably that you can interact
with them and as I said, in this case,

00:24:37.490 --> 00:24:39.370
to click on it, to read more.

00:24:39.860 --> 00:24:44.220
Does that mean now that we have
to bring back the Read More link?

00:24:44.550 --> 00:24:49.110
Yes, I think so because
just by adding this back in,

00:24:49.240 --> 00:24:50.740
even though we don't need it

00:24:50.810 --> 00:24:56.810
anymore as a link, where we have a clear--
A very, very clear signal,

00:24:56.910 --> 00:24:59.800
this is what happens when you click on
this and you're supposed to click on this.

00:25:00.820 --> 00:25:03.390
I think this is a good thing
for accessibility but of course,

00:25:03.490 --> 00:25:06.520
because we don't need it as a link,
we don't add it back in as a link.

00:25:06.920 --> 00:25:09.090
We just add it back in as a declaration.

00:25:11.460 --> 00:25:12.560
How you can do it is

00:25:12.560 --> 00:25:15.060
that you just add a spam

00:25:15.970 --> 00:25:18.770
tag for the read more

00:25:18.870 --> 00:25:22.710
and you mark it up visually
however you like it,

00:25:22.810 --> 00:25:25.270
however your design system

00:25:25.480 --> 00:25:28.000
wants the link to look like.

00:25:29.650 --> 00:25:31.450
It doesn't matter
that it's not actually a link

00:25:31.450 --> 00:25:38.020
because the whole card is clickable
and so you can just click on it.

00:25:38.240 --> 00:25:43.910
We don't want to give this

00:25:44.020 --> 00:25:46.730
also to a screen reader user
because for them

00:25:47.200 --> 00:25:51.020
it's confusing that
it's decorative as a link.

00:25:51.130 --> 00:25:55.240
It's for people who can see the card

00:25:55.540 --> 00:25:59.680
because when you're using a screen reader,
the screen reader announces

00:25:59.780 --> 00:26:01.000
this is a link.

00:26:03.350 --> 00:26:05.920
We use a little bit of ARIA here

00:26:06.650 --> 00:26:10.290
with an ARIA hidden value
of true on the span element.

00:26:10.510 --> 00:26:11.620
We take it out.

00:26:12.790 --> 00:26:18.260
Now, this is a good solution for screen
reader users who can't see the card

00:26:19.300 --> 00:26:22.870
but there's also sighted

00:26:22.970 --> 00:26:25.500
screen reader users,
so people who use a screen reader

00:26:25.600 --> 00:26:29.340
for a variety of reasons
because they have low vision or it

00:26:29.410 --> 00:26:31.970
helps them
digest information, for example.

00:26:33.110 --> 00:26:35.580
Then for them, it's a bit confusing
that there is something

00:26:35.580 --> 00:26:38.080
that looks like a link.

00:26:39.320 --> 00:26:41.080
It looks like something
you can interact with,

00:26:41.080 --> 00:26:42.930
but it's not read aloud.

00:26:43.650 --> 00:26:46.060
This can be confusing.

00:26:46.160 --> 00:26:49.990
Then to remedy this,

00:26:50.090 --> 00:26:52.600
there's another trick we can use.

00:26:53.730 --> 00:26:58.200
We can still keep it as ARIA hidden,

00:26:59.170 --> 00:27:01.670
but we give it an ID

00:27:01.970 --> 00:27:04.810
and then we link

00:27:05.110 --> 00:27:09.580
that ID to the actual link, reconnect it

00:27:10.710 --> 00:27:12.750
with ARIA described by.

00:27:12.850 --> 00:27:15.820
That means on the link tag,
you have an ARIA described by

00:27:15.920 --> 00:27:18.350
and then the ID of your readmore span.

00:27:19.660 --> 00:27:23.390
What this does is
it doesn't look any different visually

00:27:23.790 --> 00:27:28.360
but what it does is that it makes it
so the read-more is announced

00:27:28.460 --> 00:27:33.570
when a screen reader like reads the link.

00:27:34.270 --> 00:27:37.940
It would say link to link--

00:27:38.470 --> 00:27:41.440
I'm really bad-- I don't know--
I don't have it memorized so which screen

00:27:41.510 --> 00:27:45.410
reader would read it out
but it would basically be link rare birds

00:27:45.510 --> 00:27:49.120
to see that is the headline
and then read more

00:27:49.220 --> 00:27:52.720
because the description ARIA described by
is always read out last.

00:27:52.960 --> 00:27:55.890
This is really good in this use case.

00:27:56.830 --> 00:28:00.530
That is something
where we can make it more accessible

00:28:00.630 --> 00:28:03.130
for all screen reader users.

00:28:05.130 --> 00:28:07.640
Then let's see what else we can do.

00:28:08.970 --> 00:28:09.970
Oh, yes,

00:28:10.210 --> 00:28:12.710
sorry, I forgot what the next slide was.

00:28:13.610 --> 00:28:16.050
Then in WordPress,
you're working in WordPress

00:28:16.150 --> 00:28:19.110
and so you're probably
writing a loop for this

00:28:19.480 --> 00:28:22.720
and then you're not hard
coding all the IDs.

00:28:23.290 --> 00:28:27.060
What you need is
to have a unique ID that is

00:28:27.680 --> 00:28:29.970
automatically generated by your code.

00:28:34.360 --> 00:28:38.500
One way how I do it in PHP

00:28:39.940 --> 00:28:43.970
is that I use the headline,
the title of the article

00:28:44.770 --> 00:28:48.180
that we're linking to here as the basis

00:28:48.280 --> 00:28:53.720
how I generate the ID because I assume

00:28:54.780 --> 00:28:58.090
that those titles will always be unique.

00:28:58.250 --> 00:29:00.160
I just hope that the editors work
like that.

00:29:00.260 --> 00:29:03.230
That they don't create
a lot of blog articles with the exact same

00:29:03.330 --> 00:29:04.880
headline title.

00:29:05.840 --> 00:29:11.970
I turn the headline into the title
of the article into an ID

00:29:12.070 --> 00:29:14.800
with this nifty little PHP,

00:29:14.900 --> 00:29:17.410
who is excited that we're seeing PHP here.

00:29:18.310 --> 00:29:20.680
I'm just going to explain it real quick,
but it's probably better

00:29:20.770 --> 00:29:22.610
if you get the slides and copy it.

00:29:23.250 --> 00:29:27.480
Basically, we have a variable, the title

00:29:27.750 --> 00:29:31.290
that we just get with get the title
and now we have the title of the article.

00:29:32.320 --> 00:29:36.030
Then we need to turn that article
because it has spaces

00:29:36.130 --> 00:29:39.560
and maybe some funky symbols
in there or whatever

00:29:40.040 --> 00:29:42.100
and we can't have that as the ID.

00:29:42.100 --> 00:29:45.080
We need to turn it into something
that can actually work as an ID.

00:29:45.940 --> 00:29:48.400
I'm using a delimiter as a--

00:29:48.500 --> 00:29:51.010
What I want to use as a separator
between the words.

00:29:52.510 --> 00:29:55.010
Just like a dash, a URL kind of.

00:29:56.080 --> 00:29:58.550
Then I generate the ID

00:29:58.650 --> 00:30:05.020
with basically a lot of PHP replacements

00:30:05.120 --> 00:30:08.620
and turning it into lower case

00:30:08.720 --> 00:30:11.230
then replacing all of

00:30:14.360 --> 00:30:18.530
the spaces and all of that
and with the delimiter, et cetera

00:30:18.630 --> 00:30:20.020
just copy the code.

00:30:20.170 --> 00:30:22.400
Then I can use it in my template.

00:30:22.500 --> 00:30:26.880
I can just echo
the ID in the span for the read more link

00:30:26.980 --> 00:30:30.050
and then I have a unique
ID in WordPress, which is really cool.

00:30:33.420 --> 00:30:36.720
Now we have it in a pretty good state,

00:30:36.820 --> 00:30:39.620
but there's still a lot of-
some things that we can do to improve it.

00:30:40.690 --> 00:30:44.860
What I want to talk about now
is keyboard navigation.

00:30:45.030 --> 00:30:49.400
People who use the keyboard
and how that experience would be for them.

00:30:50.030 --> 00:30:52.530
If you tap to this card now,

00:30:53.870 --> 00:30:58.930
the keyboard focus goes
to the actual link.

00:30:59.380 --> 00:31:01.880
Here, I'm showing the card

00:31:05.480 --> 00:31:07.350
with a visual keyboard

00:31:07.350 --> 00:31:09.850
focus of a dotted line
around the headline.

00:31:12.320 --> 00:31:17.060
This is fine,

00:31:17.390 --> 00:31:20.400
but it doesn't really represent

00:31:20.500 --> 00:31:22.970
that you can interact with the whole card.

00:31:23.270 --> 00:31:25.800
It's also confusing
why doesn't it go to the read more

00:31:25.900 --> 00:31:27.310
because it looks like a link.

00:31:28.770 --> 00:31:30.010
What we want

00:31:30.110 --> 00:31:33.410
is to have the visual focus
around the whole card.

00:31:34.040 --> 00:31:38.250
Here in this example, I put it around
the dotted line around the whole card

00:31:38.780 --> 00:31:42.180
and actually how we do it
is that we remove

00:31:42.520 --> 00:31:45.750
in CSS the outline on the link tag.

00:31:46.510 --> 00:31:48.930
One of the very few cases

00:31:49.040 --> 00:31:52.260
where you can do this
because we're removing it there,

00:31:52.360 --> 00:31:56.800
but we're adding it to the pseudo-element

00:31:56.930 --> 00:31:59.220
when the link gets focused.

00:31:59.640 --> 00:32:02.300
This way, when somebody taps to the card,

00:32:02.670 --> 00:32:05.170
the whole card gets the focus.

00:32:06.710 --> 00:32:08.730
That's how I do it in my project.

00:32:10.710 --> 00:32:13.720
Then also what you might want to add is

00:32:13.820 --> 00:32:17.420
you want to add also a type
of hover effect.

00:32:17.850 --> 00:32:21.360
Usually, I have a hover effect

00:32:21.770 --> 00:32:23.570
that I show

00:32:23.770 --> 00:32:26.700
when somebody hovers
with their mouth above the card

00:32:26.860 --> 00:32:29.770
but then also I add the hover effect
to the focus,

00:32:31.370 --> 00:32:33.220
